<br>
When attacked, clerics do not just shriek like frightened children and slap ineffectually at the bad guys. A cleric is not a useless member of a melee group.<br>
<br>
Wearing full plate armor, wielding a summoned hammer that procs like a mad thing, using yaulp, with maxed offense and defense, bashing, etc etc etc... We may not be warriors but clerics can certainly contribute meaningfully to a fight.<br>
<br>
Try a 3 person LDoN dungeon with a paladin, cleric, and enchanter. It is a lot of fun, but the cleric had better be up there whacking things for the group to succeed and the creatures die a lot slower when they aren't.<br>
<br>
My original post was meant to express what other working clerics here have said (thank you Elhana) - that in my opinion, the arguments over where to put AA points is theoretical until you can actually see the benefits of spending them. At that point it becomes practical. In my opinion.<br>
<br>
I can actually see exceptional heals and critical spell damage. That is a practical thing. It is little harder to see the result of an AA point spent for a small percentage time extension on buffs.<br>
<br>
Eventually many of the AA points will all manifest themselves in practical ways.<br>
<br>
For now I just giggle like a [insert socially acceptable symbol of silliness here] whenever I get a crit from my hammer proc.<br>
<br>
I didn't mean for this to turn into a soapbox thread and I apologize.<br>
